#: ../../source/api/models.rst:2
msgid "ADC Behavioral Models (models)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/api/models.rst:4
msgid ""
"The ``models`` module provides ADC forward models that convert analog input "
"samples into digital decision streams and reconstruct analog output values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/api/models.rst:10
msgid "SAR Models"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:1 of
msgid "Batch SAR conversion."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:3 of
msgid "Per-sample algorithm::"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:12 of
msgid ""
"Vectorized over samples so the whole batch runs in one Python loop of length "
"``B`` (typically 4-20 iterations), not ``N`` (typically 10⁴-10⁶)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/api/models.rst adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert
#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights of
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:15 of
msgid "Input voltage trace. Interpreted relative to ``quant_range``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:17 of
msgid ""
"Actual analog CDAC weights (MSB first). Resolution and redundancy are "
"inferred from this vector. Use :func:`sar_ideal_weights` for an ideal binary "
"or redundant array, :func:`sar_apply_cap_mismatch` for unit-cap/Pelgrom-"
"style capacitor mismatch."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:22 of
msgid ""
"ADC input and output range ``(v_min, v_max)``. This mirrors "
"``ADC_Signal_Generator.apply_quantization_noise(..., quant_range=...)``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:25 of
msgid ""
"Sampled input noise RMS, in the same unit as ``vin``. One random value is "
"added per sample before the SAR bit trials."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:28 of
msgid ""
"Comparator input-referred thermal noise RMS, in the same unit as ``vin``. A "
"fresh random value is used for each bit decision."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:31 of
msgid "RNG for sampling and comparator noise."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/api/models.rst adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert
#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights of
msgid "Returns"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:34 of
msgid ""
"**codes** -- Raw bit decisions, MSB at column 0. Pass "
"to :func:`sar_reconstruct` for the analog estimate, or to a calibration "
"routine (e.g. :func:`adctoolbox.calibration.calibrate_weight_sine`) for "
"weight estimation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/api/models.rst adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert
#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights of
msgid "Return type"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:41 of
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_convert:42 of
msgid ""
"The model does NOT include DAC settling errors, metastability delay, charge-"
"injection artifacts, or PVT drift. For those, supplement with a Spectre / "
"Verilog-A simulation."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:1 of
msgid "Linear weighted-sum reconstruction: ``codes @ digital_weights``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:3 of
msgid ""
"``weights`` are the digital reconstruction weights, which usually match the "
"analog CDAC weights in an ideal model. With mismatch, keep the two roles "
"explicit: encode with actual analog weights, then reconstruct with the "
"nominal, calibrated, or actual digital weights you want to evaluate. "
"Subtract the sample mean before spectrum analysis to remove the DC offset "
"introduced by the unipolar encoding."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:10 of
msgid "Raw bit decisions from :func:`sar_convert`."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:12 of
msgid ""
"Digital reconstruction weights. Use the nominal weights for an "
"\"uncalibrated\" output; use cal-estimated or actual weights to assess "
"calibration quality."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:16 of
msgid ""
"Output voltage range ``(v_min, v_max)``. The default preserves the "
"normalized reconstruction convention."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_reconstruct:20 of
msgid ""
"**aout** -- Reconstructed analog estimate, range ``[v_min, v_min + (v_max - "
"v_min) * sum(weights)]``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:1 of
msgid "Generate ideal binary CDAC weights, optionally with one duplicated bit."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:3 of
msgid ""
"The normalization base is the sum of all bit weights plus one LSB: ``denom = "
"sum(raw_bit_weights) + raw_lsb``. In other words, a 4-bit ideal ADC uses "
"``[8, 4, 2, 1] / (8+4+2+1+1) = /16``, not endpoint-normalized ``/ 15`` "
"weights. With one duplicated redundant bit, ``[8, 4, 4, 2, 1]`` normalizes "
"by ``20``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:9 of
msgid "Architectural resolution (number of distinct decision steps)."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:11 of
msgid ""
"If given, the cap at index ``redundant_bit`` is duplicated, yielding an "
"output array of length ``num_bits + 1``. Use to model sub-radix-2 SAR with "
"one bit of redundancy. Architectural resolution stays at ``num_bits`` — the "
"redundancy adds error-correction margin, not bits."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:17 of
msgid ""
"**weights** -- Cap weights, MSB at index 0. The denominator is "
"``sum(raw_bit_weights) + raw_lsb``. If ``redundant_bit`` is used, the "
"duplicated cap participates in both the sum and the resulting overrange / "
"correction margin."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_ideal_weights:24 of
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:1 of
msgid "Realize unit-cap/Pelgrom-style CDAC mismatch."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:3 of
msgid ""
"``sigma`` is the RMS relative mismatch of a single unit capacitor. A bit "
"made from ``n`` unit capacitors gets relative RMS mismatch ``sigma / "
"sqrt(n)``. This captures the usual ``sigma(C) / C ∝ 1/sqrt(C)`` trend: MSB "
"capacitors are larger and therefore have smaller relative mismatch than LSB "
"capacitors."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:9 of
msgid ""
"By default, unit counts are inferred from the normalized weights by dividing "
"by the smallest positive weight. For ideal binary weights this gives ``[8, "
"4, 2, 1]`` for a 4-bit ADC and ``[8, 4, 4, 2, 1]`` for a redundant array. "
"Pass ``cap_units`` explicitly for custom capacitor arrays."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:15 of
msgid "Nominal analog CDAC weights, typically from :func:`sar_ideal_weights`."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:18 of
msgid ""
"RMS relative mismatch of one unit capacitor. For example, ``0.01`` is 1% RMS "
"for a 1-Cu element; an 8-Cu MSB then has ``0.01/sqrt(8)`` relative RMS."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:22 of
msgid "Numpy random generator. Use a deterministic seed to lock one chip."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:24 of
msgid ""
"Unit capacitor counts or relative capacitor sizes for each weight. Values "
"must be positive. If omitted, they are inferred from ``weights / "
"min(weights)``."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_cap_mismatch:29 of
msgid ""
"**perturbed_weights** -- Cap weights with unit-cap-scaled gaussian mismatch "
"applied. The result is NOT re-normalized."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_mismatch:1 of
msgid "Legacy per-weight gaussian mismatch helper."
msgstr ""

#: adctoolbox.models.sar.sar_apply_mismatch:3 of
msgid ""
"This preserves the pre-0.8.2 behavior where each supplied weight receives "
"the same relative RMS perturbation. For Pelgrom/unit-cap-scaled mismatch, "
"use :func:`sar_apply_cap_mismatch`."
msgstr ""
